**Add `parseDashboardListArgs(args)` function** in `resolve.ts`:
```typescript
export function parseDashboardListArgs(args: string[]): {
  targetArg: string | undefined;
  titleFilter: string | undefined;
} {
  if (args.length === 0) return { targetArg: undefined, titleFilter: undefined };
  if (args.length >= 2) {
    // Two args: first is always the target, second is always the filter.
    // Normalize bare org slug to org/ format so parseOrgProjectArg treats
    // it as org-all (dashboards are org-scoped, project is irrelevant).
    // This supports: `sentry dashboard list my-org 'Error*'`
    const target = args[0].includes("/") ? args[0] : `${args[0]}/`;
    return { targetArg: target, titleFilter: args[1] };
  }
  // 1 arg: disambiguate
  const arg = args[0];
  if (arg.includes("/")) return { targetArg: arg, titleFilter: undefined };
  if (looksLikeTitleFilter(arg)) return { targetArg: undefined, titleFilter: arg };
  return { targetArg: arg, titleFilter: undefined }; // bare slug (backward compat)
}

/** Detect if a string looks like a title filter vs. a project slug */
function looksLikeTitleFilter(s: string): boolean {
  // Glob characters → definitely a filter
  if (/[*?\[]/.test(s)) return true;
  // Contains spaces → title, not a slug (slugs use dashes)
  if (s.includes(" ")) return true;
  return false;
}
```

**Key insight:** When 2 args are provided, a bare first arg like `my-org` is always the org slug (since the second arg is the name filter). We auto-append `/` to normalize it to `org/` format. This lets `parseOrgProjectArg` produce `org-all` mode, which `resolveOrgFromTarget` handles by returning the org directly. This gives us:
- `sentry dashboard list my-org 'Error*'` → target=`my-org/`, filter=`Error*`
- `sentry dashboard list my-org/ 'Error*'` → target=`my-org/`, filter=`Error*`
- `sentry dashboard list my-org/my-project 'Error*'` → target=`my-org/my-project`, filter=`Error*`

**Extended cursor format** to support mid-page resume:

Server cursors look like `1735689600000:0:0`. We extend with `|afterId` when the filter fills `--limit` partway through a server page. The `afterId` is the **dashboard ID** of the last item we processed — a stable marker that survives insertions/deletions between requests:

- `1735689600000:0:0` — standard, resume from next server page
- `1735689600000:0:0|42` — resume mid-page: re-fetch this server page, skip items up to and including dashboard ID `42`
- `|42` — resume mid-page on the first page (no server cursor)

```typescript
/** Encode a cursor with optional dashboard-ID bookmark for mid-page resume. */
function encodeCursor(serverCursor: string | undefined, afterId?: string): string | undefined {
  if (afterId) return `${serverCursor ?? ""}|${afterId}`;
  return serverCursor;
}

/** Decode an extended cursor into server cursor + resume-after ID. */
function decodeCursor(cursor: string): { serverCursor: string | undefined; afterId: string | undefined } {
  const pipeIdx = cursor.lastIndexOf("|");
  if (pipeIdx === -1) return { serverCursor: cursor || undefined, afterId: undefined };
  const afterId = cursor.slice(pipeIdx + 1);
  const serverPart = cursor.slice(0, pipeIdx);
  return { serverCursor: serverPart || undefined, afterId: afterId || undefined };
}
```

**Single code path in `func()`:**

```typescript
const contextKey = buildPaginationContextKey("dashboard", orgSlug)
const rawCursor = resolveOrgCursor(flags.cursor, PAGINATION_KEY, contextKey)
let { serverCursor, afterId } = decodeCursor(rawCursor ?? "");
const glob = titleFilter ? new Bun.Glob(titleFilter.toLowerCase()) : undefined;

// Always cap perPage at API_MAX_PER_PAGE (server silently caps anyway).
// When filtering, use max page size to minimize round trips.
// When not filtering, use the smaller of limit and max to avoid over-fetching.
const perPage = glob
  ? API_MAX_PER_PAGE
  : Math.min(flags.limit, API_MAX_PER_PAGE);

const results: DashboardListItem[] = [];
let cursorToStore: string | undefined;

for (let page = 0; page < MAX_PAGINATION_PAGES; page++) {
  const { data, nextCursor } = await listDashboardsPaginated(orgSlug, {
    perPage, cursor: serverCursor,
  });

  // When resuming mid-page, skip items up to and including afterId
  let skipping = !!afterId;
  const resumeAfterId = afterId;
  afterId = undefined; // only applies to first iteration

  for (const item of data) {
    if (skipping) {
      if (item.id === resumeAfterId) skipping = false;
      continue;  // skip this item either way (it was already shown)
    }
    if (!glob || glob.match(item.title.toLowerCase())) {
      results.push(item);
      if (results.length >= flags.limit) {
        // Filled limit — bookmark where we stopped
        cursorToStore = encodeCursor(serverCursor, item.id);
        break;
      }
    }
  }

  // If we stopped mid-page but consumed the very last item,
  // the real resume point is the next server page
  if (results.length >= flags.limit && cursorToStore === encodeCursor(serverCursor, data[data.length - 1]?.id)) {
    cursorToStore = nextCursor;
  }

  if (results.length >= flags.limit) break;
  if (!nextCursor) { cursorToStore = undefined; break; }
  serverCursor = nextCursor;
}

if (cursorToStore) setPaginationCursor(PAGINATION_KEY, contextKey, cursorToStore);
else clearPaginationCursor(PAGINATION_KEY, contextKey);

const hasMore = !!cursorToStore;
```

**How it works:**
- **No filter, limit ≤ page size:** Single fetch, standard pagination. Loop runs once.
- **No filter, limit > page size:** Auto-paginates across multiple server pages (e.g., `--limit 200` fetches 2 pages of 100). Same `listIssuesAllPages` pattern used by `issue list`.
- **With filter, limit filled mid-page:** Stores `serverCursor|dashboardId`. On `-c last`, re-fetches same page, scans for that ID, resumes from the item after it.
- **With filter, limit filled at page boundary:** Last item was last on page → stores plain `nextCursor`. Standard resume.
- **With filter, pages exhausted before filling:** Clears cursor. `hasMore = false`.
- **Dashboard deleted between requests:** If the bookmarked ID is gone from the re-fetched page, `skipping` stays true and the entire page is skipped. We'd resume from the next server page — losing at most one page of potential matches. Acceptable edge case for dashboards.

